26




Industries


Investment Services & Portfolio Management




Company Description


Motely Fool Wealth Management's (MFWM) separately managed account program allows clients to own individually tailored portfolios that employ a mix of strategies. Each model portfolio focuses on a particular investment strategy (such as long term buy and hold) or specific type of security (such as growth stocks). The model portfolios represent different investing strategies that enable clients to hold balanced and diverse portfolios through various stages in their lives. Based on the client's specific financial objectives and risk tolerance, MFWM creates a portfolio that allocates the client’s assets across some, or all of the model portfolios. Several of the model portfolios are inspired by specific The Motely Fool (TMF) real money portfolio services. Other model portfolios are inspired by the mutual funds managed by their affiliate, Motley Fool Asset Management LLC, whose investment personnel perform research and investment management services for MFWM. The model portfolios include: Long-term Buy and Hold; Growth Investing; Hedged Equity Investing and Equity Substitutes; Domestic Stocks; Domestic Small/Mid-cap Stocks; International Stocks; and Fixed Income.MFWM’s premium wealth management service is designed for high net-worth individuals who wish to invest in stocks, bonds and other similar securities. MFWM's product, The Snapshot, uses a third-party platform and software to provide guidance regarding retirement sufficiency, cash flow, education planning and asset allocation. The firm's product, Motley Fool Touchstone, employs a proprietary, interactive, algorithmic system, designed by personnel acting on MFWM’s behalf that is based on the Fama-French Capital Asset Pricing Model. MFWM’s algorithm and their individual advisors consider factors such as the client’s income, asset allocation, portfolio holdings, assets available for investment, investing period, time to retirement, financial goals, and need to access assets, as well as the client’s risk tolerance and preferences regarding the number of positions in his or her portfolio.




